\f0\fs32 \cf0 On this section of our NVQ we covered Web Diagram and Design covering many aspects of webpages and history of the web.  In 1989 Tim Berners Lee first inverted the Web by creating HTML as its first publishing language. He also came up with the concept of HTML tags on the the Standard Generalised Markup Language (SGML) which became the base for a lot of languages to be based on. The most up to date version of HTML is version 5.0 and like most of the HTML version uses the same tags with newer ones added in to increase the overall functionality of the language. There are several other versions of HTML such as HTML 3.2, HTML 4.01 and XHTML. XHTML is Extensible Hypertext Markup Language which is essentially like HTML except the users can invent their own set of mark up for whatever purpose they desire as long as everyone uses it. New elements and attributes can be defined and added to those that already exist enabling the user to create and embed new content for web pages.  A key thing to remember about XHTML is that it is very strict as it must have certain elements added to the code as well as have the DOCTYPE correctly added. \
