After this we got to the theory behind the Document Object Model, and its relationship to dynamic HTML, as we had previously completed it in a practical session which was used to add functionality to our websites and project. The Document Object Model is defined by W3C as \'93A platform and a language-neutral interface that allows programs and scripts to dynamically access and update the content, structure and style of a document.\'94. This allows programmers to create and build documents, navigate their structure as well as make changes to elements and content. this is referred to as dynamic HTML.\
\
After this we discussed the importance of sticking to standards and in relation to web developing we looked at adhering to the W3C standard. If the page adheres to certain w3 standards then it is more likely whenever the website has been searched for that it will be more desirable in the way it is portrayed. The w3 standard allows developers who are making websites to optimise their page rendering in order to make their pages load a lot quicker and make the website more appealing to users. Finally the w3 standards will cover you for more than 1 browser so that the user is not tied down to just one browser which increases flexibility. \
\
